# jeltz-arduino

> Your sensors will describe themselves.

Arduino library that lets devices self-describe to a [Jeltz](https://github.com/heath0xFF/jeltz) gateway. No TOML profile needed — plug in your device and the gateway discovers it automatically.

## How it works

1. You register your device's tools (sensors, commands) in firmware
2. The Jeltz gateway sends `JELTZ_DESCRIBE` over serial
3. Your device responds with its capabilities as JSON
4. The gateway generates MCP tools from the description
5. Any MCP client (Claude, local LLM via `jeltz chat`, etc.) can now talk to your device

After discovery, commands use the same simple text protocol: the gateway sends `READ_TEMP\n`, your device responds `22.5\n`.

## Quick start

```cpp
#include <Jeltz.h>
#include <DHT.h>

DHT dht(4, DHT22);
Jeltz babel("dht22_sensor", "DHT22 temperature and humidity sensor");

void setup() {
    Serial.begin(115200);
    dht.begin();

    babel.tool("get_temperature", "Get current temperature in Celsius")
         .command("READ_TEMP")
         .returns("float", "celsius");

    babel.tool("get_humidity", "Get current relative humidity")
         .command("READ_HUMID")
         .returns("float", "percent");

    babel.health("PING", "PONG");
    babel.begin(Serial);
}

void loop() {
    if (Serial.available()) {
        String cmd = Serial.readStringUntil('\n');
        cmd.trim();

        // Jeltz handles JELTZ_DESCRIBE and PING internally
        if (babel.handle(cmd)) return;

        // Your command dispatch
        if (cmd == "READ_TEMP") {
            Serial.println(dht.readTemperature());
        } else if (cmd == "READ_HUMID") {
            Serial.println(dht.readHumidity());
        }
    }
}
```

Flash this to an ESP32, plug it into your gateway, and:

```bash
jeltz start -p profiles --probe /dev/ttyUSB0
```

The gateway discovers your device, generates MCP tools (`dht22_sensor.get_temperature`, `dht22_sensor.get_humidity`), and any connected LLM can read your sensor.

## API

### `Jeltz(name, description)`

Create a device instance. `name` is used for MCP tool namespacing — keep it short, lowercase, underscores.

```cpp
Jeltz babel("pressure_line", "Pressure sensor on coolant line 3");
```

### `.tool(name, description)`

Register a tool. Returns a `ToolBuilder` for chaining.

```cpp
babel.tool("get_psi", "Get current pressure reading")
     .command("READ_PSI")
     .returns("float", "psi");
```

### `.command(cmd)`

Set the command string. Supports `{param}` placeholders that the gateway interpolates before sending.

```cpp
babel.tool("read_channel", "Read a specific ADC channel")
     .command("READ {channel}")
     .param("channel", "int", "ADC channel number", 0, 3)
     .returns("float", "volts");
```

When the LLM calls `read_channel(channel=2)`, your device receives `READ 2\n`.

### `.param(name, type, description, min, max)`

Add a parameter to a tool. `type` is one of: `"int"`, `"float"`, `"str"`, `"bool"`. `min`/`max` are optional bounds for numeric types.

### `.returns(type, unit)`

Declare the return type and optional unit. `unit` helps the LLM interpret the value (`"celsius"`, `"percent"`, `"psi"`, `"mm/s"`, etc.).

### `.health(cmd, expected, interval_ms)`

Configure the health check. The gateway periodically sends `cmd` and expects `expected` back. Default interval is 10000ms.

```cpp
babel.health("PING", "PONG");
```

### `.begin(serial)`

Start listening on the given serial port. Call this in `setup()` after registering all tools.

```cpp
babel.begin(Serial);
```

### `.handle(cmd)`

Check if a command is a Jeltz protocol command (`JELTZ_DESCRIBE` or health check). Returns `true` if handled, `false` if the command should be handled by your firmware.

```cpp
if (babel.handle(cmd)) return;  // Jeltz handled it
// ... your command dispatch below
```

### `Jeltz::arg(cmd, index)`

Static helper to extract positional arguments from a command string. Useful for parameterized commands.

```cpp
// cmd = "READ 2"
String channel = Jeltz::arg(cmd, 0);  // "2"

// cmd = "SET 3 fast"
String ch = Jeltz::arg(cmd, 0);    // "3"
String mode = Jeltz::arg(cmd, 1);  // "fast"
```

## Compatibility

| Board | Status | Notes |
|-------|--------|-------|
| ESP32 | Supported | Primary target. Plenty of memory. |
| Raspberry Pi Pico W | Supported | 264KB SRAM, works well. |
| Arduino Uno/Mega (AVR) | Supported | Use `JELTZ_MAX_TOOLS=4` and `JELTZ_MAX_PARAMS=2` to fit in 2KB SRAM. |

### Tuning memory usage

```cpp
#define JELTZ_MAX_TOOLS 4    // Default: 8
#define JELTZ_MAX_PARAMS 2   // Default: 4
#include <Jeltz.h>
```

## Protocol

See the [self-describing protocol spec](https://github.com/heath0xFF/jeltz/blob/main/docs/self-describing-protocol.md) for the full wire protocol documentation.

## Dependencies

- [ArduinoJson](https://arduinojson.org/) v7+

## License

Apache 2.0

